  icon: '🐣', name: 'How chicken eggs are fertilised', domain: 'Biology · Reproduction',
  body: `<p>A chicken egg can only develop into a chick through a process that begins well before the egg is laid. Fertilisation occurs internally, inside the hen's oviduct.</p>
<p>When a rooster mates with a hen, sperm travel through the oviduct and can remain viable for up to <strong>three weeks</strong>, stored in specialised glands called <em>sperm storage tubules</em>.</p>
<p>The egg begins as a yolk released from the ovary. As it travels down the oviduct it passes through the infundibulum — the site where fertilisation occurs. If sperm are present, one penetrates the yolk surface.</p>
<p>The fertilised cell, called a <strong>blastodisc</strong>, sits on the yolk as a small white spot. Over the next 24 hours the egg acquires its albumen, membranes, and calcium carbonate shell before being laid.</p>
<p>Only a fertilised egg kept at <strong>37.5°C for 21 days</strong> will develop into a chick. Supermarket eggs are unfertilised — identical structure, no sperm present.</p>`,
